askets of Drugs, Full to their Wicked Lips -- tThe Broad Black Gateway of a Lie -- tOlympic Chariots and Much Learned Dust -- tThe Coutume De Paris -- tA Wild Night Indoors and Out -- tMere Malheur -- t“Outvenoms All The Worms Of Nile” -- t“Quoth The Raven: ‘Nevermore!’” -- t“A Deed Without A Name” -- t“Let’S Talk Of Graves And Worms And Epitaphs” -- tSilk Gloves Over Bloody Hands -- tThe Intendant’S Dilemma -- t“I Will Feed Fat the Ancient Grudge I Bear Him” -- tThe Bourgeois Philibert -- tA Drawn Game -- t“In Gold Clasps Locks in the Golden Story” -- tThe Market Place On St Martin’S Day -- t“Blessed They, Who Die Doing Thy Will!” -- t“Evil News Rides Post” -- tThe Ursulines -- tThe Lamp Of Repentigny -- t“Lovely In Death” -- t“The Mills of God Grind Slowly” -- tExplanatory Notes -- tDescription of Manuscript Copy-text -- tBibliographical Description of Published Copy-text -- tPublished Versions of the Work -- tUnrecoverable Manuscript Readings: Readings from Published Copy-text -- tEmendations in Copy-texts -- tLine-end Hyphenated Compounds in Manuscript Copy-text -- tHistorical Collation -- tAppendix0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWilliam Kirby's Le Chien d'or / The Golden Dog, a dramatic historical romance that vividly details the intertwined French and English foundations of Canada, is one of the nation's best-known pieces of nineteenth-century literature. A complicated publishing history, however, resulted in severe distortions of the text, so that each edition of the novel moved further from the author's original vision. Now, in the final work produced by the Centre for Editing Early Canadian Texts at Carleton University, editor Mary Jane Edwards returns this beloved piece of literary history to its intended form. First published in 1877, Le Chien d'or draws upon the threads of legend spun around the real-life tablet of the Golden Dog, which can still be seen in Quebec City. The novel's author William Kirby begins his tale in the 1740s, with the murder of the prosperous merchant who lived in the house that bore the tablet, and brings his work to a tragic end that coincides with the destruction of France's North American empire. Weaving historical, literary, and religious allusions together with a powerful lyricism, Le Chien d'or develops an epic narrative of the heroic past and promising future of the Dominion of Canada. Though many versions of Le Chien d'or have been published in both French and English, very few people have read what the author intended to see in print. This edition brings Kirby's unfulfilled legacy full circle by presenting a critically reliable version of his iconic Canadian novel.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLegendszQuébec (Province)zVieux Québec (Québec). 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aEdwards, Mary Jane, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aEdwards, Mary Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2012z978311127413308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2012z978311127716540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358677240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773586772423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773586772/original  a978-3-11-127413-3  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2012b2012  a978-3-11-127716-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2012b2012  aGBV-deGruyter-alles